The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the leaders of the world's developed major economies, no one can say which of them will be among the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be convergence, and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking up McDonald's stores became a standard form of protest against globalization.
But in recent times, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are becoming increasingly pointed), companies are relocating their production closer to markets where goods will be sold.
This weakens international trade growth.
Such an "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese cars. They then began producing these cars domestically.
Currently, most of the "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. But the reversal of globalized trade is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotics engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, the current critique of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
However, this evolution reflects not only the slowdown in trade growth.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more comfortable with foreign products; in some cases, they are even dependent on them, given the constantly updated electronics and the "fast fashion" at low prices that has become dominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, the current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
The disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on issues with obscure courts protecting the interests of foreign companies and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
Next comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety about this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failing and impoverished states.
Why do the populations of advanced countries fear foreigners so much?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people around the world head to advanced countries every year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we have a greater tendency to experiment quickly and superficially, rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If the participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are not inclined to provide good or simply honest service to people who will probably never return.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat you, and hoteliers lie about their facilities.
Furthermore, this little game can be interrupted.
In places where tourism has become a source of foreign income, it also becomes a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to cause a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a massive cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (visiting a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean cruise ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to replicate all the world's climates.
In fact, this ship, longer than the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourism companies, including bus and train operators, take similar precautions to ensure their clients' safety, by releasing them at a famous site for only a limited time, just long enough to take a few photos.
This type of travel puts a strain on local infrastructure capacity.
There is often not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meet only scammers who offer them overpriced trinkets or taxi rides.
The indigenous people do not appreciate large groups of tourists gathering around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor does anyone maintain a sense of trust.
One easily comes to feel a sense of nostalgia for the time when tourism was associated with long stays and prolonged interactions with very different cultures.
It would, of course, be impossible for the current number of visitors to stay for weeks or months in ancient monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more attractive experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Not long after the United States' entry into World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of setting up camp to stay at the White House for 24 days to consolidate the transatlantic alliance between Britain and deepen his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity might well be the greatest enemy of current anti-globalization populists.
